The primary constraints are: (1) Oscillatory nature: The solution varies on the scale of the wavelength $\lambda$, requiring a collocation point density sufficient to satisfy a Nyquist-like criterion (typically 10-20 points per wavelength) to prevent aliasing. (2) Re-entrant corner singularities: At corners with interior angle $3\pi/2$, the solution behaves asymptotically as $u \sim r^{
u}\Psi(	heta)$, where $
u$ depends on the boundary condition (e.g., $
u=2/3$ for Dirichlet). This results in derivatives that scale as $r^{
u-1}$, which are unbounded at the corner. The model must resolve this non-smoothness without sacrificing accuracy in the oscillatory bulk.
